node.text:
The air here is rambunctious. This neighborhood is named for the the three small peaks that jut from the flat sage scrub plain like a gathering of purulent pimples or a man's triple nipples: Tres Orejas, three ears in Spanish. I imagine that the air has a desperate need to be heard and the ears here are such good listeners that the wind feels as if it can finally open up, finally be apprehended for the first time in a long while among the chaos of the human world, and now it won't shut up.

Sometimes the wind whispers, like this morning, while I sit outside in my red Adirondack chair, drinking coffee and writing in the early morning shade of the east side of my camper trailer. But sometimes the air roars, tossing over patio furniture and carrying trash across the mesa. Yet even that is nothing compared to the wind's full wrath when it picks up mounds of dirt and flings it across the neighborhood like a child might kick dirt in your eye during a tantrum. The dust disperses in enormous clouds, traverses the flat land carrying debris and biting sand in its teeth casting a haze over distant mountains like a filter blinding us from the outside world. 

I know that personifying wind is for poets but I can't help and wonder what caused the mercurial air to create such a fuss. The wind speaks. It sings through leaves and flapping flags and tinkling chimes. It moans through mountain peaks and canyons. It whispers through pages of my notebook, through window screens and fence posts. Believing the wind is trying to tell us something is anthropocentric, of course. Obviously it exists despite us. But, still, I wonder, what does it say? If I were to take out my Google translator and type in "wind," what would be the results?

Breathe.
Breathe deeply.
Sing.
Sing loud.
Speak up.
Speak strong. 
.
.
.

I’m feeling all these same things. Except the culture in my home is very much unkind. My kids don’t get along, and there’s a lot of anger coming out. This is hard. And I’ve been feeling the privilege in school meetings for a while, ever since a real topic of discussion in kindergarten parent meetings was: Is my child too young to go skiing?🙄

@margiefran.77 know that I love all the joy and light you have brought to my children’s lives. I love our school, and pour a lot of energy and effort into it. I’ve been the first to tell people that teachers have an impossible job and they’re not going to please anyone. You’re all parents and human and are doing your best. I want to continue to help our community, it’s very hard to do that or even feel as though we’re a part of a community when our questions and concerns are ignored. I have no expectations of details. Our district is impossible. And I very much feel the need to speak up. So much of these conversations are going on in back channels and I feel that that is inappropriate. Members of our community are feeling unheard and alone and are nervous to say anything for fear of backlash. I have gone directly to my children’s teachers and feel great with what they are providing me and mine. Per my original post, my family is doing fine, I’m very concerned about the families who are not doing fine and do not feel acknowledged.

literally the first slide: our community has faced trauma. we will need to work through this together. here is a recommended reading offering for our parents on working through trauma including racialized trauma. 
Please realize we are as teachers and administrators getting inundated with questions we have no answers to. While union and district work things out. Kumbaya may not be what you needed Rachel but I have lots of new, bright eyed families who are coming into the school, and may need a different approach starting out.
Know that this is the hardest working staff I’ve ever known. We love your children like our own. For me, support looks like going directly to your child’s teacher as requested, not putting down our school on social media. Much love to you and the kids. 😘

To say we’ve done literally zero to address trauma assumes that so much we are doing isn’t actually happening. We cannot legally give out information on many specific cases, and it is very hard to be part of a school district, now more than ever.  But please know, we are not doing “literally nothing” to address our families needs. Addressing these issues through a technology platform is not easy at all. 
With that being said, I truly mean it when I say reach out to me personally. I am more than happy to help however I can.

🗣Don’t beat yourself up over past mistakes.🙅🏻‍♀️🤕
.
Now that you’ve looked at your total debt picture you’re probably frustrated. Quite frankly I remember being so pissed off at myself that I cried. 🙄 
.
Personally I wasn’t angry at the things I spent the money on. I was a full time premed student working 40-50 hours a week, doing research, volunteering, all the things they tell you to do. It was HARD. I remember using those credit cards for groceries, books, Walmart stuff, gas, the occasional Starbucks, etc. I remember being stretched to my absolute limit of problems I could handle at one time. 😰Because I was young and didn’t know better I stuck my head in the sand and told myself “just survive, you’ll figure it out later.” 😓
. 
When I calculated my debt in 2018 and cried in frustration it was because I chose to be in denial back in college. I was not equipped to handle and did not prioritize money the way I should have. Sadly, despite these failures I was still way better off than most of my friends. I saw some really horrible decisions being made but they too had the mentality of “just survive, you’ll figure it out later.” 😞
.
That’s sad. That is SO sad to me that we all felt so overwhelmed just trying to get a good education. I honestly think college was the most difficult period of my life for many reasons but finances was a big one.
.
So please...from me to you...don’t beat yourself up anymore than you already have. Your intentions were good. You did what you thought you could. 🤗
.
Life goes on and now you’re here. ❤️ You’re smarter, stronger, and ready to tackle the things you neglected. So, as we say in my first semester PA anatomy class...”it’s all going to be ok.” 🥰

node.text:
A whopping 83% of dine-in restaurants in the country have stopped operating due to the COVID-19 pandemic, according to a survey by leading food delivery company Zomato.

Of these, 10 per cent restaurants have shut down permanently and 30 per cent more are unlikely to reopen even after the pandemic is over, the survey report released on Wednesday said.

“The remaining 43 per cent, which are closed right now, are likely to open as the situation becomes better,” it added.

The report also said that the dinning industry is operating at just 8-10% of the gross merchandise value (GMV) from pre-pandemic levels.

“Nearly 60 per cent restaurateurs said they estimate to retain less than half of their original business volumes for a few months even post-COVID,” the report said.

The survey commenced on August 1 covering over 15,000 restaurants in the country, with over 1,000 restaurants in each city to understand the current state and future outlook of the industry, said a Zomato spokesperson.

node.text:
COVID-19 has brought many different emotions for many of us over the past 5-6 months.

A common one seems to be disappointment.

Maybe you’re disappointed with life looking different than before. Or maybe because it has caused many things to be cancelled or postponed - from weddings and family gatherings to festivals and traveling.

Travel is my favorite thing to do. It's the best way for me to relax and recharge.

Today is my 30th bday🎉. My husband and I would've been traveling today, but this year had other plans for us.

I'm still a bit disappointed that we aren't on a sunny beach today, and I'm allowing myself to honor that.

BUT I also recognize this is out of my control and I'm grateful for everything that is going well for us (still employed, still healthy, etc).

So, we're making the best of it. He went above and beyond to get an amazing bday gift for me 🏍.

And we made a little beach scene on our balcony to enjoy a fruity drink and the sand between our toes 🏖.

*Although the cat used part of it as a litter box almost immediately 🤦🏽‍♀️😹, he has been a good boy since then.*

So no, this is not what I had in mind for my birthday. But practicing gratitude and mindfulness definitely help manage those feelings of disappointment and put things into perspective.
♡
♡
♡
What has made you feel disappointed since the pandemic began? And how have you dealt with it? 👇🏽👇🏽👇🏽

Korsel bisa dibilang sebagai negara spesialis masakan berbasis nasi, sayur, bawang putih dan daun bawang. Banyak produk olahan mereka yang terbuat dari nasi maupun yang menggunakan bawang putih / daun bawang sebagai pengguggah selera. Salah satunya, tteokbokki ini, hidangan dari kue beras yang sudah ada dari zaman Dinasti 3 Kerajaan (pertama kali tercatat di buku resep Dinasti Joseon), sebelum Korea terbentuk, terpecah menjadi Korea Utara dan Selatan sekarang.

Saya tidak tahu seperti apa rasa tteokbokki yang paling enak / laku terjual di Korea. Karena saya belum sempat mencicipi tteokbokki yang dijual di pusat kuliner disana 🙁 . Di Indonesia sendiri, setiap restoran masakan korea punya ciri khas rasa tteokbokkinya masing2. Tetapi saya pernah baca artikel kalau tteokbokki di Korea yang ramai dibeli itu yang ada rasa bubuk karinya. Nah, tteokbokki yang saya buat difoto ini pakai bubuk kari jadi ada aroma karinya. Saya sendiri lebih prefer tteokbokki yang tidak terlalu pedas dan tidak ada aroma bumbu kari hehe.

I love these tiny purple basil flowers on my scrambled eggs. Small wins. Another small win: I’m beginning to feel like the woman I was before cancer, but better, if that makes sense. Like those deadly, toxic cells, now banished, are giving me room to breath. And literally I CAN breathe better now that that monstrosity is out of my abdomen! I’m thinking a lot about food these days, my second seafood cookbook, my hybrid cookbook-memoir, the stories to tell. Meanwhile, I’m also updating my website, h/t to the web designers, whoa what a job. And I’m reading, reading, reading. Plus my day job—working in my trucking agency. Another h/t to the drivers out there. We’re moving toilet paper, beer, and car parts. Lol. Anyway, I’m rambling here and if you’re still reading, here’s a pandemic poem I wrote. Some of you lovelies saw it on Facebook. I call it, Some Days I Forget.
.
.
.
Where is my phone? I ask myself
At least twice a day.

Before I broke down and bought 
Turquoise eyeglasses, I wandered from room to room
In search of my reading glasses.
Cheaters, I called them. They were invariably perched on the top of my head.

I forget words, birthdays, and anniversaries.

Some days I sip my cappuccino wincing at the bitterness.
No vanilla sweetener.

Some days I forget piles of sheets in the washing machine, clumped together, spun clean, discovering them days later, rancid smelling, needing another wash, spin, and rinse. Then the process repeats itself.

Some days I forget to weed the flower garden, check the mailbox, and water the topiary trees on the front porch.

Some days I forget to schedule Cooper for a groom, only remembering when his wiry coat is thick and matted.

Some days I forget to eat lunch.

Some days I forget to say please and thank you.

Some days I forget to say no.

And some days...some days...I forget I had cancer.
. 
.
.

We love being out in nature. Just walking daily, picking leaves and flowers. Gentle exposure to senses. Nature can be overwhelming with all that's going on.

This is my lovely daughter. She is on the spectrum, is highly sensory seeking, and suffers from adhd. She has taught me so much.

I struggle most days to deal with her moods, behaviors, and idiosyncrasies . . . and then she bares her heart with her sweet moments, like when she sporadically decides it's a "taking care of mommy" night. Or her creative moments like the times when she is creating mini meals or full on birthday parties for her LOL dolls. I also adore the amazing bond she has with her sister.

But homeschooling this girl is hard, y'all. I am not patient and like all of you who are trying this, I worry that her needs will not be met. Some days it's hard to get her to do the work at all. But then there are the days like yesterday when she stayed focused on two pages worth of handwriting practice. It's in those moments that I feel like we're going to be okay.

I also find that my child thrives in nature, so if you would like to learn how to use nature in your homeschooling, check out my latest blog post, which can be found in a link in my bio. Or, if you need general help with homeschooling your special needs child, I have a post filled with resources on that, too.

We can do hard things with trial and error, folks. And I do believe our efforts are building stronger bonds with our kids. 

I would love to hear about how you are incorporating nature into your homeschooling, or homeschooling your special needs child in a way that works better for you.

If there is one good thing that came out of this pandemic is all the time we are spending together as a family. 

No matter how tough it is at times with 2 kids at home and not being able to see anyone or do anything other than go for walks, I am loving these times when we are together. 

And I am SO thankful that at least we can get out! I am loving being outside, rain or sunshine! In a normal situation we would have never gone to the beach on a day like today. It was windy, it was overcast. It could have started raining any minute. But it didn’t rain! And the sun actually came out for a little bit and gave us a beautiful afternoon. We had an amazing time at the beach looking for starfish by the rocks.

So, for once, thanks covid-19. It hasn’t been ALL bad. 

PS still working on a photo of all 4 of us together. Not happening yet! 😂

Sosis Solo adalah makanan khas dari Kota Solo propinsi Jawa Tengah yang terbuat dari daging sapi atau ayam digiling kemudian dibungkus dengan dadar telur. Makanan ini diadopsi dari sosis pada zaman penjajahan Belanda yang kemudian diubah dan disesuaikan dengan bumbu dan gaya lokal masyarakat Kota Solo sehingga menjadi makanan khas daerah. Konon kabarnya Kanjeng Sunan Pakubowono X sendiri yang menggubah dan meracik pertama kalai namun sumber yang lain mengatakan bahwa Sosis Solo dibuat karena masyarakat kepengen mencoba makanan kesukaan para meneer dan noni Belanda. Meskipun hasil adopsi dari makanan luar namun rasa maupun penampilan Sosis Solo sangat khas dan berbeda dengan sosis di daerah lainya.

A strong immune system helps the body fight bacteria and viruses that can cause diseases. It is important to consume food items that fortify the body and help build anti-bodies to protect our systems especially during this period.⁣
⁣
Here's a list of 10 foods that boost your immune system:⁣
⁣
1) Garlic: Raw garlic is known to help beat skin infections and fight bacteria and viruses. Make sure to use the real stuff though and not garlic powder.⁣
2) Ginger: This root plant is a source of great antioxidants and particularly helping if mild experiencing cough or cold symptoms.⁣
3) Broccoli: Contains plenty of nutrients which protect the body from damage.⁣
4)  Sweet Potato: This is a great source of Vit A which mops up damaging free radicals.⁣
5) Low-Fat Yogurt: Low fat Yogurt contains calcium and other nutrients that can help with building and maintaining strong bones.⁣
6) Spinach: You'll find alot of nutrients in this ""super food"" which help make new cells and repair DNA.⁣
7) Watermelon: Frequent consumption of watermelon ensures a steady supply of antioxidants such as vitamin C, gluthatione and lycopene, all of which strengthen the immune system. ⁣
⁣
These listed food items are readily available and are great sources of immune boosters. If you have any chronic medical problems please discuss with your physician about your own specific health needs and which foods are safe for you to consume.⁣
⁣

node.text:
The Pandemic & Our Relationships 

These strange new times have led us to reconsider so many daily nuances, easily missed and forgotten.
They have forced us to look inside of ourselves, acknowledge, and accept that we, as humans, are as ever if not more dependent on our emotions.

Constantly engaged in ourselves and being inexpressive had become our new normal. More so, if you had 'come of an age', you didn’t speak on how you felt. 
In this week's episode, we call out those that judge us. Break the norm, no more #LogKyaBolenge

Yes, a #pandemic shouldn’t have brought us to this, but it has. So, we rise to it!

Lets talk.

Marseille was due to host ASSE - Association Sportive de Saint-Etienne on Friday in the opening game of the 2020-21 Ligue 1 campaign. But the new French top-flight season will instead start with a match between FC Girondins de Bordeaux and FC Nantes on Saturday.
-
Before the LFP announcement on Tuesday, Marseille said a trio of "suspected" coronavirus cases had been confirmed just three days before the start of the new season. The Ligue 1 club previously revealed on Sunday that three individuals within their "professional workforce" had been detected as potentially having COVID-19.

node.text:
There is nothing wrong with acknowledging our uniqueness however this pandemic has truly made it transparent how human beings need kinship to survive and thrive. This means we need communities to look out for each other. We need trust and compassion and ethical behaviour that manufactures healthy adults. 
.
In a society that has been concentrating its energy on the "me, myself and I" we've created a culture that has transmuted in our economy, our government and other influential bodies, that has lost basic value of life. We have left orphans fending for themselves. We have neglected our elderly by keeping them locked up in aged care and we have treated animals as accessories for our mere pleasure. 
.
If there is one thing we learn from this pandemic is that kinship of souls is what is going to take human beings forward. It's our respect for nature and it's greatness that will enable us to evolve into worthy beings. We are powerful if we want to be and if we had used this power  nature wouldn't have had to step in to remind us of our true potential.
. 
Stay Connected - Stay Safe
.

node.text:
As it is, the COVID-19 pandemic has hit us extremely hard. Many people have died, perhaps many more than the Indian State and its media is letting us know. Both the Union and State governments have made a worse situation even more traumatizing and nightmarish. Many have lost their jobs, and the marginalized have no choice but to remain helpless and without assistance as the parasitical and hypocritical middle classes are complaining about trivial things when there are bigger fish to fry. 

All of this building itself to become an unprecedented economic depression that would not only cause the loss of more jobs, but it may increase the misery of people that may either kill them by suicide or kill them through impoverishment. In any case, the Hindutva fascists and their ruling class masters are continuing - and will continue to - accrue more profits and more wealth at our expense, without ever coming in the way of harm like we would. 

So what do we do? We have to overthrow this parasitic, cannibalistic and oppressive system that privileges over a few over the many millions of people of our country. We have to kick out those who sit on our wealth and their fascist watchdogs if we have to improve our lot and the lot of our people, experiencing the worst consequences of the pandemic and its aftermath!

It is time for a revolution, a New Democratic Revolution!

・・・
The IY(UK) Therapy Committee has created a video and compiled a booklet with a suggested yoga programme to support recovery from Covid-19. 

As we know, Covid-19 is a highly infectious disease caused by the coronavirus. Most people infected will experience a mild to moderate respiratory illness, whilst others will show no symptoms at all. However for some the effects are severe and longer lasting.

Our aim in this yoga programme is to play some role in aiding the process of recovery. By only requiring the use of mostly basic props and furniture, we have tried to make the poses as accessible as possible for everyone.

The programme was compiled thanks to advice and guidance from Abhijata Iyengar, Lois Steinberg, Gulnaaz Dashti, Stephanie Quirk, the IY(UK) Therapy Committee, IY(UK) teachers who have experienced the virus themselves, and decades of work by BKS Iyengar and Dr Geeta S. Iyengar in medical classes at RIMYI in Pune.

See the link in our bio to access the video and booklet, which are both freely available. Please consider donating a contribution towards this and future Iyengar yoga therapy resources 🙏

Thanks to all involved in creating the programme and to @adrienne_karmaspaceyoga for designing the e-book

Hoy es el día Internacional de las fotografía, y que mejor que celebrarlo haciendo lo que más amamos. Realizando y esforzándonos cada día para entregar de manera responsable, profesional y por sobre todo con dedicación nuestro trabajo por medio de esta expresión artística.
Como siempre he dicho, esto no lo hacemos solos, y es por eso que dedico este día a todas aquellas y aquellos con quienes alguna vez he trabajado, modelos, estilistas, personal de maquillaje, equipo técnico, diseñadores etc etc. También agradezco a mis maestras y maestros que me han formado en este camino que creo que en ningún momento acabará, gracias por sus conocimientos y por todo lo que he aprendido junto a ustedes. Gracias también a mis alumnas y alumnos a quienes tengo la fortuna de enseñar todo lo que sé, gracias por que sin duda ha sido algo recíproco. Son ustedes, nuestra juventud lo que nos mantiene vivos y activos en esta maravillosa ventana llamada fotografía. 
Pese a la adversidad de estos últimos tiempos seguiremos! Claro está que seguiremos.
FELIZ DÍA A TODAS Y TODOS!!!

Can’t believe our second season of Farmer, Forester, Chef! summer camp will be over in just two short days! It’s been a crazy amazing summer! I’m so incredibly proud and thankful for the wonderful educators that joined my team this summer. It’s a pretty great feeling thinking about all the memories that were formed on this tractor and all around the farm this summer. Wow it’s been a crazy ride on the roller coaster of 2020 — but it means the world to me that my team got to provide 30 different children for six weeks a little bit of “normal” back into their daily lives.
